================================================================================
BREAKING CHANGE FIXING PLAN
Azure.ResourceManager.DesktopVirtualization
================================================================================
Total API compat errors: 288 (across net8.0, net10.0, netstandard2.0 targets)
Total unique breakings: ~96 unique errors (each repeated across 3 target frameworks)

Legend:
  [TSP]    = Fix in client.tsp (preferred)
  [SDK]    = Fix in Custom code (src/Customize/)

================================================================================
BREAKING #3: ScalingScheduleDaysOfWeekItem type changed completely
================================================================================
Affected: ScalingScheduleDaysOfWeekItem, ScalingSchedule.DaysOfWeek

Sub-errors:
  - ScalingScheduleDaysOfWeekItem: was readonly struct, now enum
  - Missing IEquatable interface
  - Missing .ctor(String)
  - Missing Equals, op_Equality, op_Inequality, op_Implicit(String)
  - Missing static properties: Monday, Tuesday, etc.
  - TypeCannotChangeClassification: was readonly
  - ScalingSchedule.DaysOfWeek: was IList<ScalingScheduleDaysOfWeekItem>, now ScalingScheduleDaysOfWeekItem?

Root cause: In the old swagger, daysOfWeek was an array of string extensible enums.
The generator created a readonly struct (extensible enum) ScalingScheduleDaysOfWeekItem
and made DaysOfWeek an IList<ScalingScheduleDaysOfWeekItem>.

In the new TSP, the @@alternateType decorator:
  @@alternateType(ScalingSchedule.daysOfWeek, ScalingScheduleDaysOfWeekItem, "csharp");
changes the entire property type from array to single ScalingScheduleDaysOfWeekItem,
and the DayOfWeek type in TSP is a fixed enum (not extensible).

Fix: [TSP]
  The @@alternateType is incorrectly collapsing the array. The daysOfWeek in the
  TSP is defined as DayOfWeek[] (array). The alternateType should target the
  ELEMENT type, not the whole property. Options:

  Option A: Remove the @@alternateType for daysOfWeek entirely. Let it generate
  as IList<DesktopVirtualizationDayOfWeek> (using the renamed DayOfWeek enum).
  Then add [SDK] custom code to add a backward-compat
  IList<ScalingScheduleDaysOfWeekItem> property with obsolete marker.

  Option B: Fix the @@alternateType to target the element type so daysOfWeek
  generates as IList<ScalingScheduleDaysOfWeekItem>. Then make
  ScalingScheduleDaysOfWeekItem an extensible enum (readonly struct) by using
  @@override or appropriate TSP decorators.

  Recommended: Option A with SDK shim for backward compat. The old extensible
  enum shape (readonly struct with IEquatable) is very different from a plain
  enum and would be extremely hard to reproduce via TSP decorators alone.

  If we accept the type change to enum (api/ baseline update), only the
  DaysOfWeek property type (IList -> single nullable) needs fixing.

================================================================================
BREAKING #5: Tags property entirely missing on VirtualApplicationPatch and VirtualDesktopPatch
================================================================================
Affected types:
  - VirtualApplicationPatch.Tags (get+set) - property does not exist at all
  - VirtualDesktopPatch.Tags (get+set) - property does not exist at all

Root cause: The TSP model for ApplicationPatch and DesktopPatch does not include
a tags property. These are child resources (not tracked ARM resources) so they
don't have tags in the new API version.

Fix: [SDK]
  Add Tags property in custom partial classes with [Obsolete] marker:

  Example (src/Customize/Models/VirtualApplicationPatch.cs):
    public partial class VirtualApplicationPatch
    {
        [Obsolete("Tags is not supported on this resource type.")]
        [EditorBrowsable(EditorBrowsableState.Never)]
        public IDictionary<string, string> Tags { get; set; }
    }

================================================================================
BREAKING #6: List/collection property setters removed
================================================================================
Affected:
  - ExpandMsixImage.PackageDependencies.set(IList<MsixPackageDependencies>)
  - AppAttachPackageInfoProperties.PackageDependencies.set(IList<MsixPackageDependencies>)
  - SessionHostAgentUpdatePatchProperties.MaintenanceWindows.set(IList<MaintenanceWindowPatchProperties>)
  - SessionHostAgentUpdateProperties.MaintenanceWindows.set(IList<SessionHostMaintenanceWindowProperties>)
  - VirtualWorkspacePatch.ApplicationGroupReferences.set(IList<string>)

Root cause: Same as Tags - new generator creates IList properties as getter-only
(the list itself is mutable). Old had explicit setter.

Fix: [SDK]
  Add partial classes with setter shims (clear-and-re-add pattern) for each:

  Example (src/Customize/Models/SessionHostAgentUpdatePatchProperties.cs):
    public partial class SessionHostAgentUpdatePatchProperties
    {
        [EditorBrowsable(EditorBrowsableState.Never)]
        public new IList<MaintenanceWindowPatchProperties> MaintenanceWindows
        {
            get => base.MaintenanceWindows;
            set { ... clear and re-add ... }
        }
    }

================================================================================
BREAKING #8: MsixImageUri type now internal
================================================================================
Affected: Type 'Azure.ResourceManager.DesktopVirtualization.Models.MsixImageUri'
does not exist (made internal).

Root cause: The TSP generator made this type internal. It was used as the input
parameter for HostPoolResource.ExpandMsixImages() which also no longer exists
as a resource method.

Fix: [SDK] (@@access decorator was tried but did not work - type remained internal)
  Add a public stub class in src/Customize/Models/MsixImageUri.cs:
  Make the generated internal partial class public by adding a custom partial
  with public visibility, or create a new public class wrapping the internal one.

================================================================================
BREAKING #12: HostPoolResource.ExpandMsixImages moved to extension method
================================================================================
Affected:
  - HostPoolResource.ExpandMsixImages(MsixImageUri, CancellationToken)
  - HostPoolResource.ExpandMsixImagesAsync(MsixImageUri, CancellationToken)

Root cause: The operation was moved from HostPoolResource instance method to
ResourceGroupResource extension method (Expand/ExpandAsync) with different
parameter types (ExpandParameterBody instead of MsixImageUri).

Fix: [SDK]
  Add backward-compat overloads on HostPoolResource in
  src/Customize/HostPoolResource.cs:

    [Obsolete("Use ResourceGroupResource.Expand() instead.")]
    [EditorBrowsable(EditorBrowsableState.Never)]
    public virtual Pageable<ExpandMsixImage> ExpandMsixImages(
        MsixImageUri msixImageUri, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        // Forward call to the new extension method pattern
    }

  Note: MsixImageUri must be made public first (see Breaking #8).
  The forwarding requires extracting ResourceGroupResource from the
  HostPoolResource, which may be complex.

